      },
      "source": [
        "## 4. Careful words: what I can and can't claim\n",
        "\n",
        "**What I can claim:**\n",
        "- Observed associations and grouped comparisons within this 30,000-row, 32-client anonymized\n",
        "  starter slice, over a fixed trailing-90-day window — nothing more.\n",
        "- Directional patterns: individual continuous signals (position, CTR, word count, age,\n",
        "  freshness, engagement) show near-zero linear association with short-term movement in this\n",
        "  slice, while `content_type` shows a real, sizeable gap in decline rate. That's a decision-support\n",
        "  finding — it tells a reviewer or a future model where to look first, not a guarantee that\n",
        "  acting on it improves outcomes.\n",
        "- That `trend_direction` / `trend_pct` are useful as the outcome I'm trying to explain here — but\n",
        "  per the data dictionary's label-trap warning, I will never feed them back in as input features\n",
        "  in any model I build later.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What I cannot claim:**\n",
        "- Causation. I ran no experiment. I cannot say any signal *causes* decline or growth, or that\n",
        "  changing it would produce a recovery.\n",
        "- Generalization beyond this starter slice. This has not been checked against the ~79M-row\n",
        "  warehouse release or its other clients — the pattern could look different at full scale.\n",
        "- Anything about Google's ranking algorithm. These are FlyRank's own observed search and\n",
        "  engagement metrics, not a window into how Google actually ranks pages.\n",
        "- That \"declining\" here is a validated future outcome. `trend_direction` is a bucket computed\n",
        "  from the current 90-day window, not a confirmed forward-looking label — a stronger version of\n",
        "  this project would define decline as a *future* outcome (e.g. features from the prior 90 days\n",
        "  predicting movement in the next 30), which is future work, not what these numbers show."
      ]
    },
